recently begun to be investigated systematically. The experiences of those at a legal, social, and cultural disadvantage allow us to go beyond the image propagated by legal institutions and offer a view “from below” of Jewish communal life and Jewish law as it was lived.Examining the interactions between gender and law in medieval Jewish communities under Islamic rule, Oded Zinger considers how women experienced Jewish courts and the pressure they were under to relinquish their monetary rights at court and at home. The tactics with which women countered this pressure, ranging from exploiting family ties to appealing to Muslim courts, expose the complex relationship between individual agency, gendered expectations, and communal authority. Zinger concludes that more than money, education, or lineage, it was the maintenance of a supportive network of social relations with men that protected women at different stages of their lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCairo Genizah. 0aCourtszEgyptxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewish courtszEgyptxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewish marriage customs and riteszEgyptxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewish womenzEgyptxSocial conditionsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewszEgyptxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMarriage (Jewish law) 0aMarriage lawzEgypt. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aCairo Geniza.  aFustat.  aIslamic law.  aJewish courts.  aJewish history.  aJewish law.  aJewish women.  aJews of the Islamic world.  aLaw and Society.  aMuslim courts.  acommunal history.  adaily life.  adivorce.  agender studies.  aheir.  alineage.  alived experience.  amarital disputes.  amarriage.  amedieval Egypt.  aproperty rights.  astories.  awidow widowhood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 20